Banking Binary Classification Problem¶

Problem¶

We would like to predict if given a bank client, are they likely to make a term deposit or not at the bank.

Dataset: bankingInfo.csv - if output == yes, then the client has made a term deposit at this bank, else they have not.

Project was built using the bc_ml_breast_cancer_pred.ipynb and the deep_learning.ipynb files provided by Dr. Sambriddhi Mainali along with the A hands-on introduction to feed-forward neural networks using Tensorflow and Keras Github Repository by Dr. Badri Adhikari found here.

3.1 Return to Un-Normalized Data, Split, and Normalize¶

To begin we will be using a backup copy made of the data before I normalized it, I had made a copy before then that was called downsample_backup. This is because it is best to normalize data normally after your split it into your train and test sets to prevent data leakage. We will then split the data into the train and test sets then normalize just the X_train set for our model using mean normalization. This should help our model learn better since neural networks prefer values between 0 and 1 while preventing leakage.

In [4]:
# Shuffle Data
banking_data = banking_data.sample(frac=1)

# Split Data into Test and Train Sets
X = banking_data.drop(['output'], axis = 'columns')
y = banking_data['output']

index_20 = int(0.2 * len(X.index))  

# Split into validation (20%) and training (80%)
X_test = X.iloc[:index_20, :]
y_test = y.iloc[:index_20]

X_train = X.iloc[index_20:, :]
y_train = y.iloc[index_20:]

# Normalization of the data 
min = X_train.min(axis = 0) 
max = X_train.max(axis = 0) 
X_train = (X_train - min) / (max - min)
X_test = (X_test - min) / (max - min)

# Review the normalized data plots
for i in range(len(X_train.columns)):
    plt.hist(X_train.iloc[:, i])
    plt.title(f"Column {i}")
    plt.show()

3.2 Build a Regression Model with 1 Neuron¶

In [5]:
regression_model = Sequential()
regression_model.add(Dense(1, input_dim = len(X_train.columns), activation='sigmoid'))
#len(X_train[0, :])
#Check for cycles in the Sequential Model
regression_model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
callback_a = ModelCheckpoint(filepath = 'regression_best.hdf5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only = True, save_weights_only = True, verbose = 1)
callback_b = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode='min', patience=20, verbose=1)
history_regression = regression_model.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_data=(X_test, y_test), epochs=100, batch_size=10, callbacks = [callback_a, callback_b])

Review of Additional Training¶

I went back after running all 7 models and since the regression model had the highest and closest accuracy, precision, recall and f1 scores I decided to see if additional training would improve the model or lead to overfitting. This model does not appear to be overfit at this time, the early stopping flag stopped the training after an additional 51 epochs. The accuracy and precision improved a little while the recall began to drop. This is to be expect because often in model as the precision increases the recall value will drop.

# constructing a neuron model
deep_4_1_model = Sequential()
deep_4_1_model.add(Dense(4, input_dim = len(X_train.columns), activation='relu'))
deep_4_1_model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

#Check for cycles in the Sequential Model

callback_a = ModelCheckpoint(filepath = 'deep_4_1_weights.hdf5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only = True, save_weights_only = True, verbose = 1)
callback_b = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode='min', patience=20, verbose=1)
history_4_1 = deep_4_1_model.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_data=(X_test, y_test), epochs=100, batch_size=10, callbacks = [callback_a, callback_b])

# constructing a neuron model
deep_32_16_8_1_model = Sequential()

deep_32_16_8_1_model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

#Check for cycles in the Sequential Model

3.7 Graduate Questions¶

1) Discuss what architecture (how big) you do need to overfit when you have output as additional input feature.
You do not need a very large architecture to overfit the model when you include the output as an additional input feature. In fact you can create an overfit model with just one neuron when output is included as an input feature, which makes sense if you think about it. By including the output as a feature you have essentially given the model the answer key to the test. It will not learn how to make generalizations because it did not learn how to make any generalizations. The model learned to just look at the output feature for what value it should predict. I tested this below using the a few different model sizes, starting at 13 neurons in 3 layers so an 8-4-1 model, then 5 neurons in layers as 4-1 model, and finally a single neuron logistic regression model. All models were overfit within only a few epochs with 100% accuracy.

def my_predictions(model, data):
    data = pd.DataFrame(data)
    numOfLayers = len(model.layers)
    w = [None]*(len(data.columns))
    
    for i in range(len(data.columns)):
        w[i] = model.layers[numOfLayers-2].get_weights()[0][i]
    bias = model.layers[numOfLayers-1].get_weights()[1]   
    z = 0
    
    for i in range(len(data.columns)):
        z = z + data.iloc[:, i] * w[i]
  
    z = z + bias
    result = 1 / (1 + np.exp(-z))   
    return result

Phase 3 Conclusion¶

In this phase I split my data into 2 sets for training and testing. I shuffled the data after loading and then the testing set was made up of the first 20% of the data while the training set was made up of the remaing 80% of the data. I then built and tested 7 models with different neural network architectures using all using these training and testing sets. All models were set to train for at most 100 epochs with the early stopping flag set to stop the training early if the val-loss does not improve after 20 epochs to prevent overfitting the models. The 7 models I built included:

  1. Logistic Regression Model
  2. Neural Network Model (2-1)
  3. Neural Network Model (4-1)
  4. Neural Network Model (8-1)
  5. Neural Network Model (8-4-1)
  6. Neural Network Model (16-8-1)
  7. Neural Network Model (32-16-8-1)


On initial review all appear to have similar results of about 71%-73% accuracy but when you look at the additional evaluation metrics such as precision, recall and f1 score you can see that some models are better than others. For example the Logistic Regression model performed better in some ways than the larger architectures. It might have had the lowest accuracy overall but the Training and Validation Accuracies are quite close together which shows that the model was not accidentally overfit. It also has the highest recall and F1-Scores of all the models, and the precision is close to the recall score as well. This indicates that the balance and completeness of the true positives is good. Precision measures the ratio of correct positive predictions out of all positive predictions that were made. Recall is the measure of the total true positives divided by the total number of true positives and false negatives. The recall in our training data and testing data is quite different though, in the training data it is quite low indicating that there is a high number of false negatives. Typically the closer the higher precision gets the lower recall becomes which can be seen in some of the larger models that as the accuracy and precision creep up the recall and F1 score drop. Finally the f1 score is the way to combine the precision and recall into one measure. This score is also best in the Logistic Regression model which is why I decided that this is best model over all because it is the most consistent in identifing the correct true positives. While the accuracy overall is the lowest I think in this problem identifing the people who are most likely to make term deposits is more useful to the bank marketers callers than correctly identifing everyone's final decision. In the other models, with the recall dropping along with F1-Score this means that the model is less likely to miss potential positives and gives the marketers a better list of customers they should contact about their term deposit accounts.

An important note is that the other models are not bad and if I had more time I would be making more training adjustments, and running additional training sessions to determine if we could improve accuracy as well as the other evaluation metrics. I do not believe that the logistic regression model is the absolute best model that could be produced, especially since it still has a rather low accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score compared to other models I've built but I do believe that out of these 7 models this one is closest to being the most useful to the bank in determining which customers to contact in their next term deposit marketing campaign.
